<title>USA: Georgia gains 23,500 new jobs in March.</title>
<headline>Georgia gains 23,500 new jobs in March.</headline>
<dateline>ATLANTA 1997-04-18</dateline>
<text>
<p>Georgia gained 23,500 jobs in March, with most of the growth in trade and services, state Labor Commissioner David Poythress said Friday.</p>
<p>Wage and salary employment rose to 3.56 million in March, an increase of 0.7 percent from February.</p>
<p>&quot;Most of the new jobs are seasonal in nature, associated with the coming of Spring,&quot; Poythress said. &quot;I expect a steady increase in seasonal employment over the next several months.&quot;</p>
<p>Trade and services added 17,600 jobs, while construction added 1,200 and manufacturing gained 1,100 jobs.</p>
<p>Seventy percent of the new jobs were in Georgia's seven major metropolitan areas. Urban areas and their jobs increases from February to March were:</p>
<p>--Albany, up 500 jobs to 59,600.</p>
<p>--Athens, up 1,100 jobs to 73,200.</p>
<p>--Atlanta, up 11,300 jobs to 1.93 million.</p>
<p>--Augusta, up 300 jobs to 194,300.</p>
<p>--Columbus, up 1,400 jobs to 112,600.</p>
<p>--Macon, up 900 jobs to 147,300.</p>
<p>--Savannah, up 700 jobs to 132,100.</p>
<p>For the year, Georgia employment grew by 73,100 jobs or 2.1 percent to 3.48 million.</p>
<p>((--Jane Sutton, 305-374-5013))</p>
